#. type: Title ##
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:61
#, no-wrap
msgid "How does regenerative agriculture help?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:64
msgid ""
"Farmers who use regenerative farming methods cooperate with nature. They "
"grow plants using methods that revive ecosystems. These methods are complex "
"and various, because each is unique to the ecosystem, soil characteristics "
"and climate of a farm."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:66
msgid "Some common regenerative agriculture principles, however, include:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:68
msgid "Create permacultures"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:71
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  * A permaculture is an ecosystem that is self-sufficient and "
"sustainable.\n"
"* Carefully manage animal grazing\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:74
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  * Livestock should gradually move across the land to graze and fertilise "
"the soil, rather than staying in one place to degrade soil and be fed from "
"troughs.\n"
"* Go organic\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:77
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  * No use of synthetic, chemical fertilisers nor herbicides.\n"
"* Grow ‘cover’ crops\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:80
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  * Winter-friendly crops are grown between harvests to cover and protect "
"the soil and increase its nutrient density.\n"
"* Compost\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:83
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  * Anything grown that cannot be used is returned to the soil.\n"
"* Reduce or eliminate tillage\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '  * '
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:86
msgid "Tillage is the process of digging up soil in preparation for growing crops."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '  * '
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:86
msgid ""
"Tillage disrupts soil, reduces its ability to retain water and nutrients, "
"and increases erosion."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:87
#, no-wrap
msgid "How does regenerative agriculture work in practice?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:90
msgid ""
"Was all that information a bit overwhelming? I’m a lifelong city boy with no "
"agricultural experience, so I know how you feel. I recently lived on a small "
"farm called Witchwood, however, which is a great example of regenerative "
"agriculture in action."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:92
msgid ""
"![Aerial view of Witchwood farm in Goongerah, East Gippsland, Australia, "
"including trees, sheds and a solar panel ](/assets/uploads/farm.jpg)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:94
#, no-wrap
msgid "*© Jill Redwood*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:95
#, no-wrap
msgid "Witchwood, Goongerah"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:98
msgid ""
"Witchwood farm (above) is a 22-acre farm in the small valley community of "
"Goongerah, 340km east of Melbourne, Australia. Witchwood is owned by Jill "
"Redwood, who also fights to protect the area’s high biodiversity with "
"[Environment East Gippsland](http://www.eastgippsland.net.au/)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:100
msgid ""
"When Jill bought the land in 1983 it was a bare, lifeless field. She "
"gradually added trees, gardens, and fences, creating an organic farm with "
"chickens, geese, goats, and horses. Jill lives as sustainably as possible, "
"which has influenced Witchwood’s design."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:101
#, no-wrap
msgid "Witchwood’s basic rules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:104
msgid "Don’t use chemicals"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '  * '
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:108
msgid "Allow complex soil ecosystems to interact as nature intended."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:108
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  * Chemicals kill natural bacteria that benefit soil, roots, and carbon "
"capture.\n"
"* Don’t overgraze\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:111
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  * Allow grass to grow, die down, and create soil.\n"
"* Don’t export manure\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '  * '
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:113
msgid "Keep it on the farm for soil nourishment."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:114
#, no-wrap
msgid "How did Jill do it?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:117
msgid ""
"I arrived on Jill’s beautiful farm after Melbourne’s long 2020 COVID-19 "
"lockdown. Jill has worked hard to create an environment of thriving "
"ecosystems and organic ingredients, but her journey was quite simple."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:119
msgid ""
"‘When I got here, the degraded soil was hard and I didn’t find many worms’ "
"explains Jill. ‘That was the first thing to fix, so I planted loads of "
"native and European trees — they’re both useful. It felt obvious to use "
"natural methods, which seemed to work well. Nature can do the job of "
"chemicals, sprays and artificial fertilisers, if you give her a chance.’"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:120
#, no-wrap
msgid "OK, but is regenerative agriculture practical on a bigger scale?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:122
#, no-wrap
msgid "Brown’s Ranch, North Dakota"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:125
msgid ""
"[Brown’s Ranch](https://brownsranch.us/) is a 5,000-acre farm in the "
"USA. During the mid-1990s, owners Gabe and Shelly Brown suffered four years "
"of weather-related crop failure and began experimenting with no-till "
"farming, to retain soil moisture and reduce fuel costs. Next, the farm "
"stopped using man-made fertilisers, fungicides, and pesticides and started "
"growing a wider variety of crops. The movement of cattle between pastures "
"was also changed, so that each pasture is left empty after grazing to "
"regenerate for at least 360 days."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:127
msgid ""
"As a result, Brown’s Ranch is now a successful business that sells ‘cash "
"crops’, such as corn and wheat, as well as grass-fed beef, pork, lamb and "
"chicken, honey, vegetables and fruit. Gabe Brown is building North America’s "
"regenerative agriculture movement with [Understanding "
"Ag](https://understandingag.com/who-we-are) and he claims that the farm’s "
"regeneration has produced [‘several "
"inches’](https://www.amazon.com.au/Dirt-Soil-Gabe-Brown/dp/1603587632) of "
"topsoil in 20 years."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 2021-03-04-regenerative-agriculture-feed-world.md:129
msgid ""
"![A line of young green leaves emerge from dark "
"soil](/assets/uploads/shoots.jpg)"
msgstr ""

